Taiwanese TV Gets Taiwanized !
Eric Lin / tr. by Phil Newell
Recently the 8:00 p.m. serials being shown on television in <COREF ID="34" TYPE="IDENT">Taiwan</COREF> have shown a trend toward " Taiwanization . "
Three out of the four main broadcast stations are showing <COREF ID="86" TYPE="IDENT">prime - time Taiwanese drama</COREF> , and <COREF ID="86" TYPE="IDENT">these</COREF> are pulling in nearly three - quarters of <COREF ID="60" TYPE="IDENT">the viewing audience</COREF> .
Of <COREF ID="86" TYPE="IDENT">these programs</COREF> , Fortune is in Heaven 's Hands , broadcast by Formosa Television , stands at the top of the heap .
It is said that , along with pop music , <COREF ID="22" TYPE="IDENT">prime - time TV serials</COREF> are one of the most important elements of Taiwanese popular culture , and that <COREF ID="22" TYPE="IDENT">they</COREF> reflect social trends .
What then is the relationship between the rise of Taiwanese drama -LRB- that is , mainly in the Taiwanese dialect and focused on the lives of distinctly Taiwanese - as opposed to " mainlander " - characters -RRB- and contemporary society and culture in <COREF ID="34" TYPE="IDENT">Taiwan</COREF> ?
Do <COREF ID="22" TYPE="IDENT">these shows</COREF> reflect the real lives and aspirations of <COREF ID="60" TYPE="IDENT">the audience</COREF> ?
And what kinds of limitations exist ?
